column168: On May 6, 2014, Veolia picked up 4 x cubic yard boxes of plating waste sludge from Goodrich Corp (UTAS) in Colorado Springs, CO.  The shipment was being placed in the 10-day dock at the Veolia facility located at 9131 E. 96th Ave., Henderson, CO 80640 when the leak was discovered. A health and safety plan was completed and reviewed before emergency response work/clean up was conducted.  Floor dry was placed over the liquid that leaked on the ground.  The spill was contained and the material was repackaged into 3 x 55 gallon steel drums.  The clean up PPE and debris was placed into 2 x cubic yard boxes and profiled as debris from clean up of plating sludge.  The cubic yard box that failed contained liquid and the liquid leaked during transit.  The packaging was not rated for liquids resulting in a packaging failure and leak.  The spill was a non RQ spill.  The plating waste is comprised of 1% chromium, 1% cadmium, 0-30% caustic soda, 0-30% 5/1 salt, and 0-30% 5/2 polymer.  The RQ for cadium is 10 lbs and the RQ for chromium 5,000.  The volume of the spill did not warrant an RQ.  One pound spilled onto the ground and 1% of one pound is 0.1 lbs for the spill.
column169: The generator was contacted to ensure the waste is dry before placing into the Cubic Yard boxes for any shipments moving forward.  Packages will be inspected by generator prior to offering for shipment via highway.  Any packages with liquids will not be offered for shipment as packaged.

column168: 14:15 hours on May 6, 2014, during a routine inspection, FRA discovered that the loaded tank car, UTLX645296, was leaking crude oil (about an inch in diameter spill) on track 9 in Vicksburg Yard, near MP 140 Meridian Subdivision. All concerned were notified.  KCS dispatched a hazmat responder.  Upon arrival the responder discovered that the packing gland nut was two turns loose. The packing gland nut was tightened appropriately by the responder. It was not repacked. There was no defect found with the bottom outlet valve.  It appears that the root cause stems from the unloader or loader failing to retighten, and further, the shipper (loader) failing to identify the loose BOV packing gland nut before offering this hazmat tank car into transportation.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.      (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

On May 1, 2014 at 1540 EST, an R&L Carriers tractor trailer experienced a load shift at 2401 Northwest 69th Street in Miami, FL. The incident resulted in 5 boxes of UN3082 Environmentally Hazardous Substance Liquid NOS getting crushed by adjacent freight. Each box contained 6.5 liters of material contained in plastic jugs, which cracked due to excessive pressure from the adjacent freight and released an aggregate amount of approximately 8-10 gallons of product. The released material saturated the outer cardboard packaging, causing it to rip. An environmental contractor used absorbents to collect the released material and all waste was containerized into (2) 55-gallon drums for disposal.

column168: A roll-off truck and trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. was loading a roll-off container at a Clean Harbors’ transfer facility. During the course of loading the contents shifted and flowed over the rear of the roll-off container and spilled onto the ground. The driver immediately stopped the loading procedure. The roll-off container was then placed back onto the ground. The driver notified his immediate supervisor.  A cleanup crew was summoned, donned the proper PPE and the released material was placed back into the roll-off container and the roll off was secured. The roll-off was then reloaded onto the truck without incident and delivered to the final disposal destination. The Utah State Department of Environmental Quality was notified report #11814.
column169: The shipper was notified of the overloaded roll-off container and advised of the proper loading parameters for the container involved. The driver has been advised to inspect the load condition for overloading or uneven loading prior to loading any roll-off container and reject containers that have been loaded improperly.

column168: The spill occured during the rail portion of a COFC intermodal load in a 55 gallon container owned by J B Hunt transport.  The information provided here is preliminary; the report may be updated as new details emerge from our on-going remediation efforts.  Initial photos show a double stack of pallets of 55 gallon drums; drums on the upper pallet were not strapped down.  Motion incidental to transport rubbed a hole near the bottom of one drum resulting in a release of up to 55 gallons of resin hazardous material.  The railroad carrier reported the incident to JBH and we dispatched a hazardous materials crew to inspect and remediate.
column169: Our findings will be shared with both the carrier and the shipper; preliminarily, we have determined the spill to be shipper preventable.  JBH and railroad personnel will provide instruction to the shipper on AAR securement guidelines and will conduct random inspections to insure compliance.

column169: Although each tote was chained to the trailer, it was clearly inadequate to handle the shifting forward that occurred after the hard braking.  The driver was instructed to use better care in blocking and bracing his loads.  Additionally, the load will be transported in a van trailer going forward.

On May 4, 2014, at 0110 hours, a car inspector at the CSXT Robb Avenue Yard, Lima, Ohio noticed material leaking from the bottom outlet valve of CMPX 153002, a residue tank car of UN2426, Ammonium Nitrate Liquid. The tank car was isolated. The shipper, PCS Sales, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2014-05-04-00002.  Virgil Fowler with PCS Sales the Consignee 706-564-8423 contacted CSX and mobilized technicians from their Lima Facility to inspect and secure the leak at the Robb Avenue Yard. PCS technicians found the bottom outlet valve leaking. The bottom outlet cap was removed and any liquid below the valve was drained. The cap was cleaned and thread sealant was placed on the threads and then tightened tool tight. The shipper representative, was notified of the situation found and informed that a One Time Movement Approval OTMA would need to be obtained prior to release back into transportation.    This incident did require a special move.    NARRI: 2x(4+1+0)x(2+0) = 20  Cause code:149

column168: 5/9/14:  CR's A. Richter, Risk Management, received call from CR Stoney Creek Yardmaster at appoximately 9:00AM, advising an NS Engineer had reported to him of frost on protective housing of tank car CGTX 64460, containing the reside of Petroleum Gases, Liquefied (Isobutane, non-odorized).    While enroute to investigate, CR Stoney Creek Yardmaster had contacted the shipper/customer, Monroe Energy (Stoney Creek Yard is the serving yard for this customer) and the customer sent some personnel out to inspect the car.  Later advised they found a loose closure plug on the vapor valve, and secured the plug tool tight.    Upon arrival, CR's A. Richter noted large amount of condensation on half of the protective housing and some moisture on top of the car near said housing.  Further inspection by CR's A. Richter, and representatives from Hepaco-React noted full interior of the protective housing was wet with water condensation, and no further vapor leak originating from the vapor valve.  However, further inspection of all other valves inside housing was conducted.  When the thermometer well cap was starting to be removed, a bubble was noted from around the threads.  Cap was secured hand tight.    CR's Richter ordered car back into Monroe Energy for their blowing down of internal pressure and flaring of contents.  Car to be moved to a AAR certified shop for inspection, repair/replacement and testing of vapor valve and thermometer well, via OTMA to be submitted to FRA by Monroe Energy and/or Centennial Energy (car owner).

column168: THE DRIVER PICKED UP THE PACKAGE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION AND BROUGHT THE BOX TO THE HUB. WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE BUILDING HE GAVE IT TO A HAZMAT AUDITOR AND SAID HE THOUGHT IT MIGHT BE HAZARDOUS BECAUSE THE BOX CAME FROM A PAINT COMPANY BUT DID NOT HAVE ANY HAZARDOUS MARKINGS. THE AUDITOR OPENED THE BOX AND DISCOVERED A 96 FL OZ CAN OF URETHANE COATING AND A 1 QUART CAN OF CONVERTER. column168: 14:17 hours on May 8, 2014, during a routine inspection, FRA discovered that the loaded tank car, GATX 28720, was leaking crude oil (about an inch in diameter spill) in Vicksburg Yard. All concerned were notified. KCS dispatched a hazmat responder. Upon arrival the responder determined that the lading was sourcing from BOV to nozzle flange connection. The BOV was cleaned with degreaser and the flange bolts tightened. Clean sorbent pads were subsequently placed under the BOV and checked after some time to verify that the leak had stopped. column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column25: Savage Services, c/o Statoil Marketing + Trading US, Inc.
column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Human Error
column168: On 05/09/2014 at 08:29 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered STAX 10730, a loaded tank car, UN 1267 Petroleum Crude Oil, with wetness on the top and sides of the tank car. The shipper Stat Oil Marketing + Trading US, Inc. was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-05-09-00071. A CSXT Response Contractor, EP+S of Vermont, the Buffalo Branch was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection the manway cover gasket was abraded and leaked product, this was caused by the Manway Swing Bolt Retainer Pin Seal, the tail of the seal was pinched between the manway cover and the nozzle causing a gasket failure. EP+S of Vermont replaced the manway cover gasket, re-secured the manway cover and wiped down the sides of the tank car.  Shipper representative was notified of the situation found and the replacement of the manway gasket. The release was secured and the car was release for transport.       Cause Code: 662 -    What: Manway, Hinged + Bolted  Where: Connection between Manway Nozzle and Manway Cover  Why: Manway Swing Bolt Retainer Pin Seal, tail of seal pinched between cover and nozzle   NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0)  = 100
column169: No additional comments.

column168: While offloading a van trailer a non-bulk 55-gallon steel drum container fell from the trailer landing on concrete floor inside secondary containment. The impact of the falling drum caused it to rupture and release approximately 30 gallons of material inside the secondary containment area. Clean Harbors Emergency Response personnel responded to the immediate area, placing the damage container into a Salvage Drum and absorbing the spilled material. All material collected in the response was containerized and sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: It was determined that this specific liquid drum was accidently double-stacked at the original loading facility.  The General Manager at the original loading facility was notified and directed to investigate why the drum was double-stacked.  It was determine a new employee who assisted in loading the van trailer was not aware of Clean Harbors double-stacking policies. All loading personnel were reminded of the double stacking policies for future loads.

column168: When the driver pulled onto the scale at the consignee, he noticed a few drips coming down the drain hose from the crash box on the top of the cargo tank.  There was no visible product in the crashbox.  The slight incline of the scale may have forced any product down the drain tube.    There was a slight indication of some dried residue.  The driver said he had checked the top of the trailer twice a day enroute and didn't notice any leakage.  When they opened the dome, they found  that part of the gasket was slightly misplaced and may have allowed some seepage.
column169: Since the shipper had closed the dome after loading and put their seal on it, we notified the shipper of the incident to make sure the plant operators verify that gasket is properly placed when closing the dome for future loads.

column168: The driver was using a pump to transfer product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  When the digital readout on the storage tank was registering 82.5% full, the storage tank overflowed < 1/2 gallon before driver could shut down.  It went on side of the tank and was wiped up with a spill pad.  Since the hose was still full of product and the driver was using a pump, it was not an issue of too much air pressure.
column169: The customer put a safety block on the tank until the level monitor could be checked for accuracy.

column168: CN Mechanical Department employee noted an odor coming from tank car UTLX 902603 (Residue: Last Contained Butadienes, Stabilized , UN 1010) during  switching operations at the CN Kirk Yard, Gary, IN. All appropriate departments were notified and tank car was isolated. CN's response team responded noting the vapor valve was not closed and the shipping plug was less than tool tight. The vapor valve was then closed and the shipping plug was tightened. A new seal was applied to the protective housing and the tank car was released for movement.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A tanker picked up a partial load of flammable liquid and returned to the ten day storage lot with no incidents.  The following morning, a strong odor was coming from the tanker trailer.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and found the dome lid had a defective gasket, as the dome could be tightened but was still emitting the odor.  The contents were then transferred to another tanker which then proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.  The tanker with the defective gasket was taken to a maintenance facility for replacement of the dome lid gasket.
column169: The only release was vapor into the air at the facility--no liquid spill.  The driver tightened the dome as tight as it would go at the time of pickup, but due to the defective gasket it was not completely sealed.  Better dome gasket inspection will be done by all drivers and mechanics in the future.

column168: The forklift operator was loading a pallet onto the dock and misjudged the depth of his forks. His forks were sticking through the opposite side of pallet and punctured a drum. Immediately after the puncture, the drum was turned onto it's side to reduce further release. Sorbent pads were used to clean up material and placed with the drum into an overpack for later disposal. Due to the hazard of material, package specifications were not able to be obtained.
column169: This particular employee was counseled on the importance of proper forklift operating procedures. Specifically in the area of moving short skids with the forklift and paying attention to fork depth. This incident will be used along with similar incidents as a training tool for other employees.

column168: An inbound BNSF train inspection in the railyard revealed entrained tank car UTLX 203496 emanating a commodity odor. Results of an immediate inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder indicated that the applied McKenzie liquid valve was the odor source with a small amount of liquid commodity surrounding the liquid valve's threaded mounting connection. The liquid valve connection was tight. This valve was removed to examine its threaded area. The responder reported that the sealant applied to its threads was dry and thus under performing as a good sealant. The responder cleaned the threaded area and applied new sealant to its threaded area. The liquid valve was then re-secured. Non-evaporating spillage was wiped. UTLX 203496 was isolated in the railyard for additional monitoring. At 1300 hrs. PDT, 5/15/2014, UTLX 203496's liquid valve was re-inspected and no evidence of any further commodity leakage was observed. FRA Movement Approval FRA-14050374 granted to transport UTLX 203496 to the consignee for unloading and then to a qualified repair facility.

SJ Transportation picked up a drum load of waste from Safety-Kleen Linden, NJ destined for SK Smithfield, KY as Transporter #2. En-route to Smithfield it was discovered that a drum was leaking. Upon discovery of the leaking container, the driver contacted the SJ dispatch office who in turn contacted the customer (Safety-Kleen). Their parent company Clean Harbors dispatched an Emergency Response crew to manage this leaking container and the subsequent clean up.    It was discovered that one drum shipped by Koehler Inst Co Bohemia, NY was leaking. The drum had a quarter inch hole on the side of the drum near the bottom rim and appears to be from internal corrosion. The drum was isolated, over packed and all contamination was contained and cleaned-up. During the clean up 9 drums of absorbents and PPE waste was generated. The response from initial notification to final clean up lasted approximately 8 hours.

The package was dropped in handling.  Examination of the inner container revealed a ruptured seam which allowed the contents to escape. The leakage was contained.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.

column168: Tank car UTLX 202912 was reported leaking commodity from its top fitting area onto its side shell while in the railyard. UTLX 202912 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. Contract responders inspecting UTLX 202912 reported finding the 3 inch threaded liquid valve in the closed position but its closure plug was not tool tight. Responders concluded that the commodity leak emanated from the closure plug orifice. The responder's inspection of the ball valve via the valve's port closure revealed commodity accumulating at the ball valve seat (liquid bypassing this closed valve). This commodity accumulation was absorbed/removed from around the valve seat. The liquid valve's closure plug was reapplied and properly tool tightened. No further commodity leakage was observed afterwards. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. The streaks of spillage on UTLX 202912's side shell were wiped. No ground impact from spillage was reported.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: I WAS CALLED BY THE BACKWALL SUPERVISOR TO COME CLEANUP A SPILL. IN FULL PPE I TOOK MY DMP CART TO DOOR 11 AND DETERMINED THAT THE BOX IN QUESTION WAS MARKED WITH A CORROSIVE LIQUID DIAMOND HAZARD LABEL. THE BOX WAS ON THE EXTENDO WITH THE BOTTOM LEFT CORNERS WET WITH A SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE ON THE EXTENDO FABRIC ITSELF. THE PACKAGE WAS PUT INTO A TRAY LINED WITH A GREEN HAZMAT BAG. I USED MY PH PAPER TO DETERMINE THAT THE PH WAS 13-14+, SO I APPLIED DISTILLED WATER AND SODIUM BICARBONATE UNTIL THE SPILLED LIQUID WAS NEUTRAL AND SAFE TO ABSORB. AFTER ABSORBING THE SPILLED LIQUID FROM THE BELT I USED MY PLASTIC DUSTPAN AND BROOM TO SWEEP UP ALL THE ABSORBENT AND PLACED IT IN INTO THE LINED SPILL TRAY. I THEN TRANSPORTED THE SPILL TRAY CONTAINING THE PACKAGE AND CLEANED UP MATERIAL TO THE DMP CAGE FOR FURTHER DMP PROCESSING.

column25: Trimac Transportation Services Inc. for Bulk Plus Logistics Ltd.
column168: Tank car PLCX 220330 positioned in the railyard's repair track for an air brake mechanical defect was reported emanating residue commodity odor. PLCX 220330 was cordoned-off awaiting inspection. Response by the Great Falls F.D. with their Haz Team and near-by consignee responders concurred with the inspection results by contract responders that the threaded vapor valve (VV) was the odor/vapor release source. The VV was loose on its riser pipe nipple's threaded connection into the valve housing plate atop the tank car. Also, the VV's closure plug was not tool tight on this closed valve. The aforementioned securement deficiencies allowed residue commodity odor/vapors to escape at this unsecured vapor valve. The responders applied Teflon tape to the exposed VV pipe nipple threads and tool tightened it. The VV closure plug was also tool tightened after Teflon tape was applied to its threaded connection. After PLCX 220330's VV was secured, the residue commodity odor dissipated. Also, non-detectable residue commodity vapor levels on the contract responder's air monitoring devices were also observed. There was no liquid commodity release associated with this incident.

column168: On May 22, 2014 at 13:00, during a routine inspection at the Veolia intransit facility, it was discovered that a drum was pressurized and bulging.  The drum was so severely bulged that Veolia EH&S deemed the drum and trailer it was on unsafe to be near by all personnel.     At 16:00, the drum top was completely blown off of the drum due to the excessive pressure that had built up in the drum.  One gallon of paint related material was released onto the trailer floor and on the top of other drums that were in the same trailer.    The drum was overpacked into a 85 gal steel drum and shipped to the destination facility for disposal.  The material that spilled was cleaned up and sent to a proper waste disposal facility.
column169: The shipper, General Electric Company, will monitor drums of the same waste type on site for one week prior to shipment.     Veolia Schenectady now inspects containers at the beginning of the day.  Until this incident, Veolia Schenectady performed only an end of day inspection of containers.  Adding the morning inspection may prevent or reduce the severity of incidents such as this.

column168: On 05/12/2014 at 06:07 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered TILX 191217, a loaded UN1267  Petroleum Crude Oil, leaking from top of the tank car. The car was isolated, CHEMTREC was notified, report 2014-05-12-00020. EP+S of Vermont, Buffalo Branch, a CSX emergency response contractor was dispatched to the yard, upon inspection the Liquid Line Valve Packing Gland Nut was found loose, and product seeping from around the valve operating stem. The shipper, United Energy Trading, LLC was notified, Mr. Clarence Vassau was advise of the problem found and the corrective action taken. EP+S of Vermont secured the release, tightened the packing gland nut 1.1/2 turns, the tank car was wipe down of residual product on the sides and released for disposition.    This did NOT require a special switch move.      Cause Code: 296  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On May 15, 2014 at 1720 hours contractors in the CSXT Radnor Yard reported a release from TCIX 16130, a loaded tank car of Suflur, leaking from the bottom outlet valve.  Contractor personnel had heated the car and were preparing to partially transload the contents because the tank car had been found to be overweight.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Duke Energy, was notified (CHEMTREC Report #145-244).  SWS Environmental, the CSXT response contractor that was already on site, replaced the secondary securement cap on the bottom outlet nozzle to stop the release.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative.  Contractor personnel also mobilized materials and equipment necessary to remediate the release.   The tank car is currently being held at CSXT Radnor Yard pending the shipper obtaining the necessary OTMA to allow the car to transport for unloading and subsequent home shop for bottom outlet valve repair.      NARRI: 2(5+1+0) x (5+0) = 60  Cause Code: 662

column168: On May 23rd at 2023 hours personnel in the CSXT Savannah Southover Yard discovered GATX81014, a loaded tank car of 2Dimethylaminoethanol leaking from top of car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Taminco was notified via CHEMTREC report number 2014-05-23-00275.  SWS, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the cause of the release was due to the liquid line closure plug being less than tool tight with the valve in the closed position. column168: Seven cubic yard boxes of debris with lead contamination were picked up by Veolia from a State of Connecticut sponsored road project. It had rained quite heavily recently but the boxes appeared OK at the time of pick up. The following morning, a Veolia employee was checking the vehicle containing the boxes that had been parked at the Veolia office overnight. He noticed a couple of boxes had become wet at their lowest point overnight. He called EH&S and the customer to report the issue and ask for guidance on how to proceed. He obtained assistance and opened the containers for further inspection. There was a significant amount of rainwater that was trapped in the liner of the boxes and it had started leaking through the liner and through the fiberboard onto the floor of the vehicle and less than a gallon below the vehicle. He took photographs of the issue, cleaned up all liquid that had leaked out of boxes, absorbed all loose liquid in the boxes, and repackaged all boxes, and sent out for appropriate disposal at the requested TSDF. Estimated duration of leak was less than a gallon of liquid outside of boxes for a period of about 12 hours (overnight).
column169: The customer was notified of the issue and was asked to prevent precipitation from entering the boxes in the future.

column168: On June 5, 2014 at 09:30 EST, a 55-gallon steel drum containing UN1710,TRICHLOROETHYLENE, 6.1, PGIII, released approximately 1/4 cup of material to the top of the drum, due to an improperly threaded bung cap. Absorbents were placed on the released material on the drum, containerized and placed in a 5-gallon bucket for proper disposal. The 55-gallon drum with the improperly threaded bung cap was over-packed and staged on site to return to the shipper. No soils, drains or waterways were reported to have been impacted by the release.

column168: ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT JOB #35148: ON WEDNESDAY, 05-21-14, AT 0958 HOURS (CTZ).  MR. TIRSO BELTRAIN OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT (EMI) RECEIVED A CALL FROM MR. JEFF MESSER OF CON-WAY TRUCKLOAD, INC. (CTI). MR. MESSER INFORMED MR. BELTRAIN THAT A CTI DRIVER HAD REPORTED THAT IT WAS SUSPECTED THAT CARGO IN A TRAILER COULD BE POSSIBLY LEAKING. THE CARGO CONSISTED OF CLASS 8, AND CLASS 5.1(8) MATERIALS.  THESE MATERIALS WERE PACKAGED IN 55 GALLON, 30-GALLON, 15-GALLON AND 5-GALLON CONTAINERS. AT THE TIME IT WAS NOT KNOWN WHICH PRODUCT(S) WERE LEAKING. THE AMOUNT OF THE RELEASE WAS NOT KNOWN. MR. MESSER REQUESTED THAT MR. BELTRAN MOBILIZE A RESPONSE TEAM TO THE LOCATION OF THE TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT TO INVESTIGATE THE MATTER AND PERFORM ANY NECCESSARY CLEANUP IF REQUIRED. MR. BELTRAN CONTACTED PATRIOT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (PES), AN EMI APPROVED ENVIRONMENTAL SUBCONTRACTOR, AND REQUESTED THAT A RESPONSE TEAM BE MOBILIZED TO THE SITE. PES PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SITE. IT WAS OBSERVED THAT NO MATERIAL HAD IMPACTED THE ASPHALT SURFACE OF THE PARKING LOT. NO STORM DRAINS OR NAVIGABLE WATERWAYS WERE IMPACTED. PES THEN OPENED THE TRAILER DOORS. IT WAS OBSERVED THAT ALL THE CONTAINERS WEER PALLETIZED. PES PERSONNEL THEN ENTERED THE TRAILER TO VISUALLY INSPECT THE CONTAINERS. SIX ROWS FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER, A 55-GALLON POLY DRUM CONTAINING SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION WAS FOUND TO HAVE A PUNCTURE HOLE (APPROXIMATELY 1/4 INCH IN DIAMETER) ON THE SIDE, APPROXIMATELY 6 INCHES FROM THE TOP OF THE DRUM. THE CAUSE OF THE PUNCTURE COULD NOT BE DETERMINED AT THIS TIME. A SMALL AMOUNT (APPROXIMATELY 1/2 CUP) HAD BEEN RELEASED AND IMPACTED A SMALL AREA ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE PALLETS OF UNDAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER (PROVIDED BY CTI) TO ACCESS THE LEAKING DRUM. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS THEN PLACED INTO A 95-GALLON POLL OVERPACK DRUM. THE POLY OVERPACK DRUM WAS THEN PROPERLY LABELED AND PLACED ON A CLEAN PALLET. A SODA ASH SOLUTION WAS THEN UTILIZED TO NEUTRALIZE AND CLEAN THE SMALL AREA ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. ONCE THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS CLEAN, THE PALLETS OF UNDAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE TRANSFERRED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL TRAILER. THE LOAD WAS SECURED, AND THE UNIT WAS RELEASED BACK TO THE DRIVER.
column169: Continue our on going efforts in driver safety/spill prevention training in preventing incidents as these from happening. Stress how important that pre and post inspections are performed. By the driver performing the pre inspection, the incident was minor. Should the leak not been detected at the time, it could have grown into a much bigger situation.

A BNSF mechanical inspection of an outbound BNSF train in the railyard revealed entrained tank car GATX 79950 emanating a commodity odor with a small amount of liquid commodity observed on its side shell. Immediate inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder of GATX 79950 determined that the leak source was at the liquid valve's bolted mounting flange connection. The responder reported finding all 4 stud bolt nuts on the liquid valve's flange connection loose (each approximately 5 full turns loose) which allowed some commodity to escape at this unsecured flange connection. The responder tool tightened these loose stud bolt nuts. Spillage on the valve housing plate was wiped along with spillage on the top side shell. Afterwards, no further commodity leakage at this mounting flange connection was observed. Intact shipper seal at the valve housing cover was replaced by BNSF seal 06157716. Response was concluded by 1715 hrs. PDT, 5//11/2014.

column168: Tank car ACFX 76880 was reported in the railyard leaking commodity which was evaporating from its top fitting area. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder relieved the internal pressure within ACFX 76880 to ebb the commodity release emanating from the liquid valve's bolted mounting flange connection. Afterwards, the commodity leak at this flange connection ceased. ACFX 76880 was monitored to ensure no further commodity leakage at now secured flange connection was evident. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. The intact shipper seal at the valve housing cover was replaced by seal TIS-5996. All spillage evaporated. column168: THE FOLLOWING CORRESPONDENCE DETAILS THE RESULT OF EMERGENCY RESPONSE ACTIVITIES CONDUCTED BY NRC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (NRC)ON MAY 6, 2014 AT THE PORTLAND TERMINAL RAILROAD LAKE YARD IN PORTLAND, OREGON.  NRC WAS CONTACTED BY UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD AT 1400 HOURS ON MAY 6TH, 2014 AND REQUESTED TO RESPOND TO THE ABOVE-REFERENCED LOCATION AFTER TANK-CAR NATX 364306 WAS FOUND DURING INSPECTIONS BY OREGON DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION RAIL INSPECTORS WITH THREE OF SIX MAN-WAY LID BOLTS UNSECURED.  NRC RESPONDED TO THE SITE WITH ONE EMERGENCY RESPONSE SUPERVISOR, ONE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TECHNICIAN AND RESPONSE VEHICLE. THE NRC CREW ARRIVED ON-SITE AT AND CHECKED-IN WITH YARD OPERATIONS AT 1445 HOURS. NATX 364306 WAS LOCATED ON TRACK 10. TRACKS 9 & 11 WERE OUT OF SERVICE UNTIL THE LEAK FROM THE MAN-WAY WAS REPAIRED. THE NRC CREW PROVIDED ITS OWN TRACK PROTECTION BY LOCKING AND BLUE FLAGGING THE NORTH AND SOUTH ENDS OF TRACK 10. NRC PERSONNEL UTILIZING SCBA'S AND NON-SPARKING TOOLS WALKED IN TO ACCESS NATX 364306 ARRIVING AT 1600 HOURS. THE REMAINING PRESSURE IN THE TANK-CAR WAS VENTED AND THE MAN-WAY OPENED REMOVING SEAL 47515905. THREE OF THE SIX MAN-WAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND THE REMAINING BOLTS REQUIRED MINIMAL EFFORT TO LOOSEN. ONCE OPEN THE MAN-WAY AND GASKET WAS INSPECTED, NO DEFICIENCIES WERE NOTED WITH THE MAN-WAY NOZZLE OR GASKET. NRC RE-SECURED THE MAN0WAY AND APPLIED SEAL 768408. NRC REMOVED THE LOCK AND BLUE FLAG PROTECTION FROM THE SOUTH END OF TRACK 10 AT 1720 HOURS AND WAS ABLE TO REMOVE THE LOCKS ON THE NORTH END OF TRACK 10 AT 1820 HOURS AND DEMOBILIZE FROM THE SITE. PROJECT OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETED AT 1900 HOURS.

column168: Incident Facts  On May 21st, 2014 at around 2:45PM Acetone overflowed from an Acetone Truck that was being loaded from VT-629.  The initial TER indicated that the release amount was 1 gallon.  However, further investigation revealed that the release may have been as high as 110gals. The Tier 2 Threshold Quantity for Acetone is 34gals and this event has been classified as a Tier 2 Process Safety Event.    Background Information  On May 21st a truck was sent to the Frankford Plant to load 6,777gals for Momentive Specialty Chemicals.  The truck had a capacity of 6,500gals.  Through discussions with the Shipper, it was discovered that order amounts often exceed the capacity of the trucks. The Shipper indicated that he misread the truck capacity as 6,700gals.  The truck capacity is determined by the Shipper inspecting the stamped capacity on the truck.  This number is often difficult to read. The Shipper set the loading meter to 6,600gals.  It is standard practice to set the loading meter at 100gals less than the capacity of the truck when the order amount exceeds the truck capacity.  As the truck approached the end of its load, the Shipper returned to the platform and was waiting for the process to complete.  The Shipper heard a noise which was followed by the inflatable hatch seal pushing up and allowing Acetone to be released from the side.  The hatch seal system is bolted in place and did not become completely disengaged.     Corrective Response  Upon identifying the release, the Shipper immediately closed the manual valve to the loading arm.  This stopped the flow and the release of material.  Once the overflow stopped, the Shipper pressed the emergency stop button to stop the loading pump from running.  The Shipper estimated that the release amount was 50 to 70 gallons. The area was washed down with water by the Shipper to remove the volatile material.  He attempted to contact the Transportation Manager, but he was unable to report to the scene due to an audit that was being performed.  The Operations Supervisor (25) reported to the scene to review the incident.  The Operations Supervisor estimated that the release was one gallon because he did not see any material on the ground or on the truck.  However, he did not ask the Shipper for an estimated release amount.
column169: Recommendations - Root Cause (Entered into ETS)  1.Reactivate the Acetone truck loading high level shutdown meters   2.Standardize how the Shipper sets the meter based on order amount and truck capacity.  Include reviewing the process of setting the meter 100gals below the capacity of the truck   3.Revaluate the process of obtaining the truck capacity and make recommendations as needed.  Involve multiple shippers in this review     Recommendations - Additional Findings (Entered into IMPACT)  1.Clearly define and communicate the proper response and communication of a Loss of Primary Containment (LOPC) Event     2.Clearly define the responsibilities of the Operations Supervisor and the Logistics Manager in regards to oversight of the day to day shipping activities     3.Assess and recommend potential on all High Level Shutdowns across all loading operations for all chemicals

column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. column168: On 5/15/2014 during an FRA inspection at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCS) Lauderdale siding in Lauderdale, MS, GATX 41036 was found with residue adhering to outside of car - emanating from manway - some residue still wet - visible from ground level. Upon learning of the situation, KCS dispatched contractors to secure and clean the package.  Upon arrival the exterior of the car was wiped clean with absorbent pads.  The manway was inspected and it was discovered that the manway bolts were less than tool tight.  The bolts were subsequently tightened.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: After an inbound BNSF train inspection in the railyard by BNSF mechanical inspectors, the inspectors reported a commodity odor emanating from entrained tank car NATX 37688. A detailed inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder revealed commodity odor/vapors emanating from NATX 37688's manway closure. The responder reported that no manway gasket was applied (manway gasket missing). The responder installed a new manway nozzle gasket, closed and properly re-secured the manway cover and applied BNSF seal numbered 06157256 at the manway closure. No liquid commodity release was reported.

At 0955ET hours, R&L Carriers contacted Emergency Response & Training Solutions (ERTS) regarding a release of an unknown amount of UN1987 ALCOHOLS NOS to a trailer and dock area from a crack, near the spout of a 275 gallon tote. No soils, drains or waterways were reported as being impacted and the product is evaporating as it releases. Initially facility personnel placed absorbents to limit any product migration. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor, 1st Response of OK. The contractor performed a product tote transfer into a replacement tote and reported that approximately 10 (ten) gallons of product was lost. 1 (one) yard of contaminated absorbents collected and was properly disposed of at the Waste Connections Landfill in Oklahoma City, OK. The R&L facility retained custody of the damaged tote for future inspection by the shipper.

column168: Prev Rollover.  Driver claims to have taken evasive action to avoid other vehicle, however, there were no witnesses and no debris to indicate such.  Tanker was breached casuing loss of 56 gallons ULSD to soil.    DOT Rollover Crash.  Single vehicle.  Driver tansported for medical and tractor towed.    Reported small release of approx 56 gallons to NRC and SC DHEC.    Action Environmental managed spill clean up.
column169: If the driver maintained control of the vehicle the rollover & product spill would not have happened.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On Sunday, May 25, 2014 at approximately 1915 hours PTRA Job281 Foreman reported that he observed product leak from the top of GATX 2833 while switching rail cars in PTRA Penn City Yard. PTRA Trainmaster Brashear responded to the scene and determined that the car was leaking from the pressure relief valve.  The car was waybilled to Merisol located approximately 1500 feet North of Penn City yard.  After consulting with PTRA Safety Director Higbie and Merisol representative Henderson the decision was made to safely move the car into Merisol under 49CFR174.50 where Merisol could isolate the car and get GATX to come out and make repairs. The rail car shows being spotted on the customer track at 2246 hours.    Merisol reported that GATX replaced the PRV and tested the car on June 3, 2014 and released by Merisol.
column169: At this time we do not know what triggered the failure in the PRV.  GATX is evaluating the device. The PTRA does not know if the shipper was contacted by Merisol to notify them of the issues with the PRV. Merisol's assistance with the car and agreement to recieve the car with the faulty PRV significantly reduced the chances of further release and other potential issues.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On May 16, 2014 at 1510 EST, Ryan Frick with U.S. Xpress contacted ERTS regarding a UN3378 Sodium Carbonate Peroxihydrate release. It was reported that 4 bags containing UN3378 are leaking in the back of a U.S. Xpress trailer (602660). It was determined that 3 50lb. bags were torn, resulting in product to be released onto the trailer floor with no environmental impact. The trailer was stationed outside a Apco Packaging, Building 2, at 9901 South 76th Avenue in Bridgeview, IL 60455. Cleanup was conducted removing product from trailer. It was determined that the facility accepted and processed the damaged bags of product at the facility.

A strong odor was reported by PTRA Manchester yard crew while switching cars in the Manchester Yard at approximately 2000 hours. PTRA RFE Farmer responded to the scene and was unable to find the source of the odor on account of a large rain event moving through the area. At 2200 hours the rain event had concluded and RFE Farmer found GATX 57904 with all manway bolts loose. Product was not observed on the car due to the rain event however a faint odor was present. The car was isolated in track 026 in the yard and M&M PRotection responsed to the scene to inspect and secure the car. M&M confirmed that all six manway bolts were loose and were the cause of the leak. The gasket was inspected and confirmed to be in excelent condition. M&M secured the manway and sealed the manway cover.
column169: The shipper SAREX USA was notified and accepted full responsibility for the failure at the loading site. They are following up with the site to ensure compliance with procedures already in place.

column168: CN transportation department employee reported vapors coming from the top of tank car GATX 61257 (RESIDUE / HYDROCHLORIC ACID) during switching operations at the CN Destrehan Yard, Destrehan, LA. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting the vapor valve was in the open position and the blind flange was loose allowing a small amount of vapors to escape. The response team closed the vapor valve and tightened the blind flange. The leak stopped.  Tank car released for movement.

column168: CN Transportation department employee noted a steady stream of product leaking from the top of tank car UTLX 23491(L / Methanol, UN 1230) during switching operations CN Baton Rouge Yard, Baton Rouge, LA. The product was observed coming from the area of the combination house.  The combination housing was secured with seal # IMTT 175381.  Upon opening the combination housing, product was observed coming from the flange below the liquid line valve.  The bolts were tightened and leak stopped.

column168: While enroute, the driver took a break at one of our facilities.  He noticed that product was leaking out of a washout cap on the cargo tank.  He replaced the washout cap and the gasket and then did a surge test to make sure there was no further leakage before continuing.

column168: A release of UN2874, Furfuryl alcohol came from a damaged 55 gallon metal drum in Cheyenne, WY. The trailer was at the scale station on I-80 when a liquid was noticed to be leaking from the trailer. Approximately 15 gallons of the material was released from the drum due to a hole on the side of the drum about half way up from the bottom. The material was released to the trailer floor and the asphalt below. It appears that a load shift caused the damage to the drum.

When driver first started to transfer product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank, product leaked out of the QRB on the discharge assembly.  Driver shut down immediately.  He was not the driver that had brought the trailer to the shipper for loading so he did not know that the first driver failed to properly inspect the trailer before loading.  It was discovered that the packing was missing in the assembly.  driver put some in and completed the unload without incident.  Driver had wiped up the leakage with spill pads.
column169: The first driver failed to follow proper procedures to pretrip the trailer before loading.  He will receive performance enhancement training on addressing pretrip inspections.

column168: A transformer containing PCB oil >500ppm was received at the Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. transfer facility at Kent, WA. The transformer was discovered to be leaking while being stored inside a trailer being prepared for shipment. An in house clean-up crew was summoned, donned the proper PPE, and remediated the impacted trailer floor and concrete below the trailer. The generated clean up waste was properly packaged and disposed of together with the leaking transformer at the original disposal destination. The Washington State Department of Ecology was notified. WSDE report # 14-1804.
column169: At the time the transformer/container was accepted for shipment no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. In order to prevent a recurrence, transformers will only be shipped/stored in trailers with secondary spill containment. Facility personnel have been counseled and received retraining on the proper handling of transformers containing liquid.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: 20 large wet acid batteries were banded together on a wooden pallet. Corrugated cushioning material was placed between the batteries for shipping. While in transportation, the metal banding used to secure the batteries to the pallet made contact with a battery terminal causing a short circuit resulting in ignition of corrugated cushioning material (placed between the batteries) and shrink wrap. Smoldering fire was isolated to the pallet. No injuries or property damage as a result of the incident. The incident was discovered during offloading of the shipment at the Veolia facility in Phoenix, AZ.
column169: This was a third party shipment to Veolia.  Veolia followed up with the broker to contact the customer requesting to eliminate the use of metal banding when it is possible in that the banding could contact the terminals of the batteries.

column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 40 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: Our driver was coming to the end of his unloading and the pump had stopped pumping, so he went upon the trailer and open the bleed valve to allow the pump to suck the remaining peroxide from the suction line into the storage tank and the tank overflow into the containment pit. He estimated the spill to be 20 gallons of 50% standard grade peroxide. There were no injury. He shut down the trailer pump and diluted the spill in the dike using water.  He notifed the site personnel and his distribution manager.  The site personnel were able to handle the diluted material in their treatment process.
column169: Driver failed to follow procedure.  He failed to confirm that the amount in his trailer can exceed the capacity of the customer's storage tank.  He also failed to monitor the tank level during the delivery.  Driver received a written warning in his personnel file and proper procedures were re-emphasized with him and all of our other drivers during our monthly safety call and issuance of incident report.

Bulk Driver was at a Ferrellgas Satellite Depo in San Marcas CA.    He was preparing to load his truck and was lifting the liquid line hose to connect to the bobtail. He had the hose in one hand and the other hand near the valve handle. He is thinks the hose got caught up on the rack when lifting the end of hose or he slipped and fell. There is a little lip on the rack.  When the hose moved the valve cracked and released propane spraying him on his chest and arms. He quickly turned around and ran and hurt his back in process of running away. He ran around the truck and shut down internal valve on the storage facility. He noticed his shirt was frozen – he had on a tank top underneath, he took both shirts off.  Bulk Driver went to Urgent Care and they called the paramedics to come get him and take him to the hospital.
column169: The employee performed proper steps to shut down internal valve when the incident occured.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While loading at customer location, a leak occurred. Apparently, a crack in the seam of compartment #4 on the tank trailer caused the leak. Approximately 1,400 gallons of gasoline were released. Romulus Fire Department responded to assess the site. The free product was contained to the concrete containment within the customer's loading area. The containment area empties directly to the facility's oil water separator system. Free product was recovered into the facility's system immediately, and did not migrate to soils or threaten to impact state waters. There were no injuries or exposures reported.

THE TRAILER-TANKAR WAS LOADED WITH HOT LIQUID ASPHALT AND IT LEAKED OUT OF TANKER INTO THE MEDIAN. HAMILAN TRUCKING INC (OWNER) PUMPED REMAINDER OF LIQUID INTO ANOTHER TANKER. THE SPILL ASPHALT WAS SCAPPED OFF GROUND AND HAULED AWAY. ASPHALT WAS CLEANED UP COMPLETELY BY YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP INC., G-5305 NORTH DORT HWY., FLINT, MI 48505. LIQUID ASPHALT DID NOT CONTAMINATE GROUND.

column168: On May 21, 2014, during the examination of export documents offered for transport. The carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed on an invoice that container FSCU932807-3 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (UN 1950 AEROSOLS). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded. We immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. The same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and afterward released for transportation

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc had arrived at customer site, placed the vacuum trailer into containment loading area for purposes of loading.  The driver hooked up fitting and hoses and had just began loading when the three inch to the two inch reducer fitting leaked causing less than one gallon to spill in the containment berm loading area.  The vacuum was immediately shut down and loading operations halted.  Absorbent material was applied to the spilled material and contained in containment area.  All absorbent and spill debris was placed in the over pack drum and secured for shipment to the designated treatment facility.
column169: At the time the pre trip inspection was performed, no evidence of damage to the fitting or hoses was observed. It turns out the crack was internal and not visible to the driver during routine inspections.  All hoses and fittings will be inspected by maintenance shop for wear and or structural damage.  Drivers will be retrained to closer review all fitting and hoses during pre and post trip inspections.

column168: NOTICE RECVD ON 5/12:We have been informed that tank number SIMU2501981 is currently at GPA in Savannah. It appears that while working the vessel this tank fell off the bomb cart and started leaking.  There has been mention that the caps on the tank were not firmly secure. REPORT FROM CERES: Sunday, May 11th, 2014  Garden City Terminal  Savannah, GA  Ø Received call from Brad Z, who advised me that there had been a 20ft  Export tank tip over during the vessel operation.  He also advised that the contents of the tank were leaking and that the tank was marked a class 3 Hazard.  At that time  he was in contact with the superintendent and was enroute to the terminal.  Both Brad and the superintendent had their HazardMat books and located the UN # on the tank.  o   The Port and Fire Company were on scene.  Incident commander for Ceres was the super, for the Hazard Area, the Fire Chief  o   The driver of the yard tractor was not reporting any injuries at the time.  Ø Made call to Dan Hall, left message on cell phone number.  Ø Received a call about 20 minutes later.  Brad advised information received from the super, that there was minor diesel fuel leaking from the truck, and cargo leaking and heading toward  outlet to the river.  Hazmat contract was on scene and attempting to keep product from the water.  Ø Received call from Brad advising that he had the all clear from the Fire Chief and that no product reached the water.  He also stated that the Fire Chief stated that the leak was from a loose valve.  Further details will be reported in the Pollution incident report and the Property Damage report.  BCP/Emergency Action Plan  Ø Phone communication were handled properly and quickly  o   No call was made to Patrick as both Brad and I estimated the financial exposure to be less than $100,000 and there were no serious injuries.  o   The vessel continued to work  o   All clear was communicated to Dan’s cell voice message service.  Monday, May 12, 2014  am  Ø Brad, Greg  are working with Rene to tie up loose ends  Ø Product labeling is in question.  Produce is more that Class 3  Ø Tank and Cargo were on NYK bill of lading   Ceres processes were followed and BCP/Emergency Action Plan work effectively.  CALL REPORT TO PHMSA: 200 YARDS FROM SAV RIVER. 25 GALLONS DISCHARGED FROM OVERFLOW VALVE. NO FIRE. 15 GALLONS OF GAS LEAKED FROM TRUCK. NO CONTAMINATION TO WATERWAY.

column168: Unit 1 was pulling unit 2 west bound on I-20 Service Rd.  Unit 1 was making a right turn to go South bound on E. Loop 338.  Unit 1 was traveling at an unsafe speed causing it to roll on its side bringing the coupled Unit 2 over as well.  Unit 1 and Unit 2 sustained right side distributed damage from impacting the road and the shoulder.  Unit 1 and Unit 2 came to a stop in the right hand (West most) lane on E. Loop 338 just past the intersection with I-20 Service Rd.  No fuel was lost from the cargo tank.  A small amount of diesel fuel and motor oil from Unit 1 was lost to the roadway.  This was cleaned up along with the debris from the wreckage.  The driver was taken to a local hospital where he was treated and released for a minor laceration to the hand.
column169: Company shall review incident investigation and root cause analysis with all drivers to provide heighten awareness of roll-over potential, and preventative measures.    Company is exploring and testing stability control systems to help in the prevention of incidents of this nature.

column168: Unit 1 towing Unit 2 was traveling East on FM2438.  Driver of Unit 1 Towing Unit 2 failed to control speed and lost control of truck at "T" intersection. Unit 1 towing Unit 2 crosssed over Alt-90 onto the right grassy shoulder of Alt-90.  Driver used faulty evasive actions causing Unit 1 to crash into a fence, then causing Unit 1 and Unit 2 to overturn.  The Units came to rest in the field off Alt-90 facing East. No diesel fuel was lost from the cargo tank as a result of the crash. Emergency Services were called and secured the scene.  Company personnel and equipment responded to the scene, transferred the diesel fuel over to another truck.  The overturned truck was then uprighted and removed from the scene.
column169: Company shall review incident investigation and root cause analysis with all drivers to provide heighten awareness of fatigue, high aim steering, and safe driving behavior.

column168: A RCO yard job shoving rail cars into a yard track derailed 10 railcars including tank car GATX 81889. The cause of this derailment was attributed to lateral drawbar force on curve excessive due to car geometry. GATX 81889 derailed towards its side with its bottom outlet valve (BOV) damaged (sheared off) releasing commodity. The local F.D. and BNSF mechanical responders were able to position a wooden plug at the BOV's exposed orifice which ended the release of escaping commodity. Containment was placed under the BOV while GATX 81889 was awaiting commodity transfer into another suitable tank car. The observed ground impact area of spillage was excavated. The excavated sites were backfilled with native soil and then clean rock ballast applied atop. The ground impact areas were also sampled for traces of any remaining commodity presence.    On 6/13/2014, contract responders transferred the commodity within GATX 81889 into another suitable tank car without further incident. Afterwards, GATX 81889 was triple rinsed, cleaned and purged of all hazardous material.
column169: No additional comments.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: The load shifted when the truck stopped suddenly in heavy traffic.  The load shifted suddenly to the front of the trailer.  The batteries were packed on pallets and when the load shifted the heavy batteries slammed into each other causing the plastic housing on some of the batteries to crack.  The batteries were filled with sulfuric acid and this acid started to leak into the trailer after the load shifted.       Nassau County Hazmat Team was called to the site to do the initial clean up and containment.  Miller Environmental Group was also dispatched to the scene to do the final clean up.  Soda Ash and water was used to neutralize the acid that had leaked into the trailer and out onto the roadway an shoulder.  The debris in the trailer was placed into a 55 gallon drum for disposal.  The impacted soil was neutralized with soda ash and water and placed in a 55 gallon drum for disposal.       Each battery was then inspected for damage.  If it was damaged the acid was drained into a 55 gallon drum and the battery was wrapped in an acid absorbing packing material.  The damaged and undamaged batteries were separated and repackaged.   The trailer was decontaminated one more time once the load was removed using soda ash and water.  All waste was placed in a 55 gallon drum for disposal.       On June 20, 2014 the waste was taken to PSC Northland Environmental in Province, RI for disposal.  A total of 1 drum of sulfuric acid, 2 drums of soil, acid, soda ash and water were generated.  Also 27 drums of contaminated packing material and other debris was generated.
column169: The batteries could be packaged more securely to prevent this type of loss from happening again.

column168: This was a motor vehicle crash and had nothing to do with air transport.  The form would not let me skip the air transport section so I had to check some boxes to get this to go throughthe syste.    The Linde vehicle was traveling on I-75  on a wet roadway when traffic came to an abrupt stop due to another motor vehicle accedent about  a mile ahead.  The Linde vehicle slid ont eh wet roadway, withthe trailer swinging out to the side which struck a stopped auto.  The auto impacted the pressure build coil under the trailer ripping the piping loose from the trailer.  The piping contained a small amount of argon gas and th gas was released.  There was not release from the trailer itself, only the piping.  The car ended up wedged under the trailer.  No injuries to the Linde or auto driver, minor injury to a passenger in the auto.
column169: Continued training of drivers in defensive driving and planning ahead for such situations.    This report was originally filed by e-mail and due to additional information and problems withthe file formatting, was refiled using the online system

column168: HUMAN ERROR RESULTED IN A TANKER ROLLOVER ON THE INTERSTATE. TANK VESSEL INTEGRITY WAS NOT COMPROMISED HOWEVER DUE TO THE TANK BEING ON ITS SIDE PRODUCT RELEASED THROUGH THE TANK PRESSURE RELEASE VALVE. EMRGENCY RESPONSE WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. INITIALLY, DIKES AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL WERE UTILIZED TO MITIGATE THE RELEASE. REMANINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERED TO ANOTHER TANK AND HAULED AWAY. ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY WAS CONTRACTED TO CLEAN UP SITE AND REMOVE CONTAMINATED SOIL.
column169: CONTINUE TO EDUCATE AND TRAIN DRIVERS ON TANK SAFETY AND ROLLOVER PREVENTION.  UTILIZED THIS ACCIDENT AT FUTURE SAFETY MEETINGS TO DEMONSTRATE WHAT CAN BE DONE TO PREVENT THESE TYPES OF ACCIDENTS IN THE FUTURE.

column168: DRIVER RETURNING WITH TRANSPORT TRAILER CONTAINING RESIDUAL AMOUNT OF GAS FROM CUSTOMER SITE, LEFT ROADWAY, LOST CONTROL AND ROLLED OVER. TRAILER SEPARATED FROM TRACTOR UNIT AND ROLLED DOWN A GRASS EMBANKMENT APPROXIMATELY 50 FEET FROM ROADWAY CAME TO REST ON ROOF. IMMEDIATE CALL TO LOCAL POLICE, AND FIRE DEPARTMENT AND AMBULANCE SERVICE. STATE OF NH DOT RESPONDED TO SCENE AS INCIDENT COMMANDER. DUE TO INHERENT RISK OF THE PRODUCT REPRESENTATIVES FROM EXPRESS NATURAL GAS WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE. A SERVICE PROVIDER FOR THE TRAILER MAINTENANCE AND ANOTHER TOW TRUCK COMPANY WERE CALLED TO SCENE FOR RECOVERY EFFORTS.         ASSESSMENTS OF TRAILER SHOWED SIGNIFICANT DAMAGE TO CHASSIS AND SUSPENSION, AND BOX FRAME HOSING THE 4 CYLINDER TANKS. MOUNTING BOLTS ON FOUR CYLINDERS HAD BEEN SHEARED OFF DURING THE ACCIDENT AND THE REAR FRAME OF THE CARGO WAS SEPARATED.      VISUAL INSPECTION AND USE OF GAS DETECTORS VERIFIED NO GAS WAS LEAKING AND THE INTEGRITY OF THE TANKS. REPRESENTATIVES FROM XNG, ABENAQUI CARRIERS, NHSP WORKED TO OPEN REAR COMPARTMENT DOORS SO MANIFOLD PRESSURE AND TEMPERATURE COULD BE TAKEN TO DETERMINE EXACT AMOUNT OF PRODUCT REMAINING. WITH 500 PSI REMAINED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THIS COULD BE SAFETY VENTED BEFORE THE MOVING THE CONTAINER FOR TRANSPORT. THE AREA WAS SURVEYED FOR POTENTIAL IGNITION SOURCES. THE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED THROUGH THOUGH THE MANIFOLD VALVES LOCATED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.
column169: RECOMMENDATIONS FOR IMPROVEMENT ARE TO PROVIDE MORE RECURRENT TRAINING FOR DRIVERS CONCERNING FATIGUE AND FATIGUE RELATED ISSUES.
column172: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

column168: A Quality Carriers Inc., claim 41455, tanker experienced the release of a estimated 50 gallons of Dowanol (UN3092) product from a external valve that was found leaking onto the asphalt and an approximate 4ft.x4ft. patch of soil.    The driver utilized a containment bucket to collect the leaking material. Cleanup contractors were dispatched to the site to secure the release, clean the impacted area and conduct a transfer of product to another tank truck.     Response personnel reported that the bolts on the drain valve were tight and that the gasket was bad.     Absorbents were applied to the impacted asphalt and worked in thoroughly. The impacted soil was hand excavated. Clean up waste generated created 1-55gal. drum of waste. Remaining product was offloaded onto another tanker.

column168: WHILE ATTEMPTING TO GRAVITATE MIX XYLENE ONTO THE MMI-2805 FROM THE AROMATICS UNIT, THE CARGO HOSE RUPTURED. PRELIMINARY INVESTIGATIONS INDICATE THAT A BARGE MISALIGNMENT BY THE TANKERMAN CAUSED THE CARGO HOSE TO OVERPRESSURE WHEN MATERIAL WAS DETERMINED TO NOT BE ENTERING THE DESIGNED BARGE COMPARTMENTS, PROMPTING A REQUEST FROM THE BERTH PERSON TO THE TANK FIELD CONTROLLER TO "START/STOP" THE PUMP TO ESTABLISH A FLOW, PER NORMAL OPERATING PROCEDURES. UPON HOSE RUPTURE, THE PUMP WAS IMMEDIATELY STOPPED, ALL ASSOCIATED VALVES WERE BLOCKED AND THE FLOW OF MATERIAL CEASED. BOTH CURTAIN AND OIL SPILL BOOM WERE DEPLOYED. THE BARGE DECK WAS CLEANED UTILIZING A PORTABLE PUMP AND OIL SPILL PADS. THE SPILL WAS ESTIMATED AT 5.3 GALLONS TO THE WATERWAY AND 4 BARRELS TO THE DECK OF THE BARGE.
column169: FROM NOW ON, IN THE EVENT THE PRODUCT DOES NOT GRAVITATE, WE EXPECT THE DOCKWALKER AND THE TANKERMAN TO ACTUALLY TRACE OUT THE PIPING TO MAKE SURE ALL VALVES ARE OPEN BEFORE PROCEEDING WITH TRANSFER. SHOULD BE A "HANDS-ON" EXERCISE, NOT A DISTANT/VISUAL EXERCISE. IF PRODUCT STILL DOES NOT GRAVITATE, WE WILL INTRODUCE NITROGEN/AIR INTO THE HOSE AT THE RISER VALVE AND VERIFY THE PIPING IS OPEN FROM THE DOCK RISER VALVE TO THE LOADING COMPARTMENT.

column168: ON 5/30/2014 @ 1200, Landstar contacted ERTS regarding a UN1133 release of approximately 5 gallons to the back of a tractor trailer. ERTS dispatched a network contractor who contained the release. The contractor found 33 pails of adhesive damaged and was advised to take them for disposal.

OUR DRIVER WAS STARTING TO DROP A LOAD OF FUEL. HE HAD MADE ALL HIS CONNECTIONS AND HAD MADE HIS FILL CALCULATIONS. AS HE WAS BEGINNING TO UNLOAD THE FUEL HAD CAUSED THE HOSE CONNECTIONS (CAM LOCKS) TO COME LOOSE FORM THE UNLOADING FITTING (DROP GUN). WE BELIEVE AT LEAST ONE OF THE CAM LOCKS WAS NOT COMPLETELY CLOSED. BEFORE THE DRIVER COULD GET THE INTERNAL VALVES CLOSED, WE BELIEVE 20 TO 25 GALLONS OF REGULAR GASOLINE HAD SPILLED FROM THE NOW OPEN  ENDED HOSE LYING ON THE ASPHALT. AFTER GETTING THE INTERNAL VALVE SHUT THE DRIVER RAN AND BROKE OPEN THE SPILL KIT ON THE TRAILER. AT THIS TIME THE DRIVER TOOK THE SPILL BOONS AND PLACED THEM AT THE STORM DRAIN AT THE DRIVEWAY ENTRANCE TO THE GAS STATION. HE ALSO PLACED A CALL TO DISPATCH AND THEN CALLED 911. AS A RESULT OF THE 911 CALL THE COUNTRYSIDE FIRE PROTECTION DISTRICT, JEFF STEINGART, CHIEF, 600 N. DEERPATH DR. VERNON HILLS IL 60061, TELEPHONE 847-367-5511 RESPONDED AND PLACED BOONS AGAIN AT THE STORM DRAIN AS THE DRIVER HAD PLACED BOONS AT, AS WELL AS DOWNSTREAM ALONG THE OPEN STORM WATER RUNOFF DRAINS. AT THIS TIME I AND COMPANY OWNER JAMES SMITH WERE NOTIFIED AND CAME TO THE SCENE. IN ADDITION OUR ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP COMPANY, SET ENVIRONMENTAL INC, 450 SUMAC ROAD, WHEELING IL 60090, TELEPHONE 847-537-9221 WAS DISPATCHED AND BEGAN THE CLEANUP AFTER ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE.
column169: PER OUR COMPANY POLICY AND UNION AGREEMENT THE DRIVER WAS SUSPENDED FOR A PERIOD OF TIME, AND RECEIVED A FINAL WRITTEN WARNING. UPON RETURN THE WORK THE DRIVER WAS RETRAINED ON THE UNLOADING PROTOCOLS PER OUR COMPANY POLICY. THE DRIVER IN ADDITION WAS SUBJECTED TO A VALIDATION UNLOADING CRITIQUE IN ORDER TO DETERMINE ADHERENCE TO COMPANY POLICY. WE ALSO HAD A SAFETY MEETING FOR ALL EMPLOYEES SOLELY COMPRISED OF THE EVENTS OF THIS ACCIDENTAL RELEASE. THE MEETING FOCUSED ON THE FAILURES, CAUSES AND PROTOCOLS DESIGNED TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. THE UNLOADING WERE AGAIN DISSEMINATED TO ALL DRIVERS WITH THE EXPECTATIONS OF COMPLETE COMPLIANCE.

column168: When freight was loaded it rubbed against the trailer wall, ripping the bags, causing release of product.    All damaged containers were placed into a poly drum and cleanup debris was placed into a separate poly drum. When released product was cleaned it, wood chips were also swept up with the product. Released material is incompatible with organic materials and reacted with the wood chips causing it to ignite.     Fire Dept was contacted to assist with containing the fire and an Emergency Response team was sent out to assist with neutralizing and remediating the debris. All product was  placed into a salvage drum and was handled according to all local, state, and federal regulations.

column168: ON MAY 6, 2014, AT APPROXIMATELY 7:00 AM CDT, A BOBTAIL TANKER OPERATED BY TEXAS FUELING SERVICES, INC. WAS TRAVELING IN NEAR THE 2400 BLOCK OF FARRELL ROAD WHEN THE DRIVER WAS FORCED TO SWERVE TO AVOID A COLLISION. THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE UNIT AND OVERTURNED IN THE DITCH ADJACENT TO THE ROADWAY. AS A RESULT OF THE IMPACT, APPROXIMATELY 2,600 GALLONS IF RED DYE DIESEL FUEL WERE RELEASED TO THE SOIL DITCH. EMERGENCY RESPONSE: LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. UPON ARRIVAL FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL DISPATCHED A CREW FROM MASTERS ARS (MARS) TO ASSESS AND REMEDIATE THE SITE. ON MAY 6, 2014, AT APPROXIMATELY 3:15 PM CDT, A REPRESENTATIVE WITH TEXAS FUELING SERVICES, INC., MR. SEAN KRAMER, RETAINED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICE, L.C. (CES), TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP OF THE SITE. BASED ON THE AVAILABLE INFORMATION THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER CONTACTED MARDS TO DISCUSS THE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS AND RETAIN THEM UNDER THE STANDARD CRS CONTRACT. REGULATORY NOTIFICATION: ON MAY 6, 2014 MARS PERSONNEL CONTACTED CHEMTELL TO MAKE VERBAL NOTIFICATION OF THE RELEASE. CONFIRMATION NUMBER 20141429 WAS ISSUED TO THE RELEASE. THE CRS INCIDENT MANAGE LATER CONTACTED THE TEXAS COMMISSION ON ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY TO DISCUSS THE RELEASE AND WAS PROVIDED WITH THE CONFIRMATION NUMBER 197869. CONCLUSIONS: FOLLOWING THE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS, NO VISUAL OR OLFACTORY EVIDENCE OF DIESEL FUEL WAS OBSERVED AT THE SITE. RESULTS FROM THE SAMPLING EVENT RETURNED BELOW STATE LEVELS EXCEPT SAMPLE CONF 4 WHICH WAS LATER RESAMPLED AND GROUND TO BE BELOW THE METHOD OF DETECTION. BASED ON THESE RESULTS, IT APPEARS THAT THE CORRECTIVE ACTION WAS SUCCESSFUL AND NO FURTHER ACTION SHOULD BE REQUIRED. CES RECOMMENDS THAT THE INCIDENT BE CLOSED. CURA EMERGENCY SERVICE, L.C. APPRECIATES THE OPPORTUNITY TO PROVIDE YOU WITH OUR PROFESSIONAL EXPERTISE IN THIS MATTER, IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE FEEL FREE TO CALL US AT (972) 378-7333.
column169: MARS PERSONNEL ARRIVED AND ASSESSED THE SITE. CREW MEMBERS OBSERVED EVIDENCE OF RED DYE DIESEL IN APPROXIMATELY 300 YARDS OF DITCH LINE. COUNTY PERSONNEL DEPLOYED SAND TO BOTH SIDES OF THE DITCH TO PROVIDED CONTAINMENT AND PREVENTS THE FURTHER MIGRATION OF FREE PRODUCT. LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL AND TEXAS FUELING SERVICES, INC. PERSONNEL DRILLED AND TAPPED THE OVER TURNED TANKER AND TRANSFERRED THE REMAINING PRODUCT INTO A NEW TANKER. ONCE THE DAMAGED UNIT WAS UP RIGHTED AND REMOVED FROM THE SITE, MARS PERSONNEL BEGAN COLLECTING FREE STRANDING PRODUCT WITH A VACUUM TRUCK. TCEQ PERSONNEL ARRIVED TO ASSESS THE SITE AND LEFT THE SITE SHORTLY AFTER DETERMINING THAT ONSITE ACTIVITIES WERE SATISFACTORY. ONCE VACUUM OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETE, MARS PERSONNEL BEGAN EXCAVATION OPERATIONS. ALL EXCAVATED MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED AND CONTAINERIZED INTO ROLL-OFF CONTAINERS FOR TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL. MARS PERSONNEL ENSURED THE SITE WAS CONTAINED AND DEMOBILIZED FROM THE SITE. ON MAY 7, 2014, MARS PERSONNEL RETURNED TO THE SITE AND CONTINUED EXCAVATION OPERATIONS. ALL EXCAVATE MATERIAL WE COLLECTED AND CONTAINERIZED INTO ROLL-OFF CONTAINERS FOR TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL. CREW MEMBERS CONTINUED EXCAVATION OPERATIONS UNTIL NO VISUAL OR OLFACTORY EVIDENCE OF DIESEL FUEL COULD BE OBSERVED AT THE SITE. ONCE EXCAVATION OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETE, MARS PERSONNEL COLLECTED FIVE CONFIRMATION SAMPLES FROM THE EXCAVATED AREA AND ONE BACKGROUND SAMPLE FROM THE SURROUNDING AREA FOR LABORATORY ANALYSIS. ON MAY 8, 2014, MARS PERSONNEL RETURNED TO THE SITE AND CONTINUED EXCAVATION OPERATIONS. AGAIN, ALL EXCAVATED MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED AND CONTAINERIZED INTO ROLL-OFF CONTAINERS FOR TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL. CREW MEMBERS CONTINUED EXCAVATION OPERATIONS UNTIL NO VISUAL OR OLFACTORY EVIDENCE OF DIESEL FUEL COULD BE OBSERVED AT THE SITE. ONCE EXCAVATION OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETE, MARS PERSONNEL COLLECTED FIVE CONFIRMATION SAMPLES FROM THE EXCAVATED AREA AND ONE BACKGROUND SAMPLE FROM THE SURROUNDING AREA FOR LABORATORY ANALYSIS. UPON RETURN OF THE RESULTS FROM THE SAMPLING EVENT, IT WAS OBSERVED THAT CONFIRMATION SAMPLE CONF 4 RETURNED AT ELEVATED LEVELS. ON MAY 30, 2014, THE AREA WHERE CONF 4 WAS TAKEN WAS RESAMPLED, RESULTS FROM THE SECOND SAMPLING EVENT RETURNED AT LEVELS BELOW THE DETECTION LIMIT. ON JUNE 3, 2014, MARS PERSONNEL RETURNED TO THE SITE AND BEGAN SITE RESTORATION ACTIVITIES. CREW MEMBERS BACKFILLED THE AREA AND BEGAN WORKING THE AREA TO RETURN THE SITE TO ITS PREVIOUS GRADE. MARS PERSONNEL CONTINUED RESTORATION ACTIVITIES UNTIL LACK OF DAYLIGHT PREVENTED FURTHER WORK. CREWS DEMOBILIZED FOR THE DAY. ON JUNE 4, 2014, MARS PERSONNEL RETURNED TO THE SITE TO CONTINUE SITE RESTORATION ACTIVITIES. CREWS CONTINUED SITE RESTORATION ACTIVITIES. CREWS CONTINUED BACKFILL AND RE-GRADING OPERATIONS UNTIL COMPLETE. MARS PERSONNEL DEMOBILIZED FROM THE SITE. ONE JUNE 5, 2014, MARS PERSONNEL RETURNED TO THE SITE. CREWS PLACED SOD OVER THE AREA THEREBY RETURNING THE SITE TO PRE-SPILL CON

column168: THE PETRO CHEMICAL TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER GASOHOL INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK. IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, HE MISTAKENLY OPENED A VALVE ON THE TRAILER PRIOR  TO CONNECTING THE HOSE TO THE STORAGE TANK. AS A RESULT APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF GASOHOL WAS RELEASED. SEVERAL GALLONS OF THE SPILLED GASOHOL MIGRATED INTO THE ROADWAY. ANOTHER VEHICLE ALLEGEDLY DROVE THROUGH THE GASOHOL AND THEN LOST CONTROL AND OVERTURNED. THE FOUR OCCUPANTS IN THAT VEHICLE SOUGHT TREATMENT AT THE LOCAL EMERGENCY ROOM WHERE  THEY WERE TREATED AND RELEASED. SWS ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIAN. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: PETRO CHEMICAL TRANSPORT, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: ON 5/19/14 DRIVER WAS LOADED WITH 7500 GALLONS OF LSD AND EN ROUTE TO DELIVERY DESTINATION IN FLEMINGTON, NJ. WHILE IN APPROACH TO THE TRAFFIC CIRCLE AT MINE ST & ROUTE 12, DRIVER TRIED TO AVOID A VEHICLE THAT ENTERED HIS PATH, WHICH RESULTED IN THE TRUCK AND TRAILER OVERTURNING. DRIVER HAD A BYSTANDER REPORT ACCIDENT TO THE POLICE, AS HIS PHONE WAS IN THE OVERTURNED TRUCK. POLICE, FIRE AND RESCUE ARRIVED AT THE SCENE FIRST. DRIVER REPORTED THE ACCIDENT TO DEBRA'S OFFICE AT THIS TIME. OFFICE THEN CONTACTED THE INSURANCE COMPANY. DEP & INSURANCE CLEAN UP CREWS ARRIVED AT THE SCENE, CONTAINING THE LEAK FROM THE TRAILER, WHICH WAS CRACKED DURING IMPACT. CLEAN UP CREWS STARTED PUMPING THE PRODUCT IN THE ROADWAY INTO A SMALL OIL TRUCK (APPROXIMATELY 1650 GALLONS) AND INTO LARGE STORAGE TOTES AND BARRELS (APPROXIMATELY 950 GALLONS). APPROXIMATELY 3901 GALLONS WAS SALVAGE AND PUMPED FROM THE TRAILER, INTO A HIRED TANKER, AND WAS DELIVERED TO ORIGINAL DELIVERY DESTINATION.
column169: DRIVERS ARE PERIODICALLY RE-TRAINED ON ROADWAY AND DELIVERY SAFETY PROCEDURES.  THEY ARE ALSO REQUIRED TO MAINTAIN DAILY EQUIPMENT INSPECTION LOGS AND EQUIPMENT MAINTENANCE.

column168: A Gateway FS, Inc. driver was assigned to retrieve a 1465 gallon anhydrous ammonia nurse tank from a farmer's field on Jamestown Road in Breese, IL after application was completed. While proceeding south on Jamestown Road the driver saw a car traveling north and moved his custom applicator rig and nurse tank partially onto the shoulder to more easily allow the car to pass. After the north-bound car passed by, the driver attempted to move his rig and tank back onto the road. The nurse tank then began to weave back and forth until it overturned and skidded along the road and into the ditch. A dirt build-up caused the liquid withdrawal valve to open slightly allowing a release of vapor. The driver called 911 and the facility manager, Tim Richter. The Breese Fire Department and Mr. Richter arrived on-scene. While Mr. Richter contacted IEMA and the NRC, the Fire Department secured the scene. After donning protective gear, the fire department closed the valve which stopped the release. The tank was then righted and the contents emptied into another nurse tank. Those on-scene noted there was no significant environmental or infrastructure damage. In addition, there were no residences or occupied structures nearby. As anhydrous ammonia becomes a gas when released, there was no product to clean-up or dispose of as waste.
column169: In the future all nurse tanks will be transported form one location to another behind company trucks. This combination is narrower which reduced and/or eliminates the need to leave the roadway on many rural roads. In addition, this form of transport will result in greater nurse tank stability. Additional training will also be instituted to reinforce the difficulties and hazards inherent in the transport of anhydrous ammonia nurse tanks. The nurse tank involved in this incident was taken to Bierman Welding in Effingham Illinois for inspection, repairs (if needed), and pressure testing. The nurse tank has since been inspected, pressure tested, and returned to our Breese facility with documentation attesting to it's condition and tank tightness.
