column168: The driver, Brian Pevito has a two stop customer delivery on this run.  He had previously delivered the first stop and was en-route to his second customer delivery stop. Brian was pulling a four compartment trailer.  The first customer received all of the product in compartment #4.  Compartment #4 was empty and Compartments #1,2,and 3 remained with the product loaded for the final destination.  This scenario adds higher risk factor for cornering maneuvers due to the change of the center of gravity. Brian had previously successfully accomplished this type of delivery in the past.  On this day there was a failure to operate the vehicle in a safe manner.  Eye witnesses described Brian's driving as operating at a speed that was not in excess.  However, with the given knowledge of his loaded trailer and his trained awareness of the road factors, such as road terrain, the speed that Brian went into the turn was indeed a little too much in excess.  The roll-over was described to be in slow motion as it happened. The tractor/trailer ended on it's side.  Two passer-bys called 911 and Apple Valley, MN police arrived within minutes of the accident.  Apple Valley police called the fire department response team.  The owner Steve Steiger was notified.  Steve Steiger contacted the Minnesota Duty Officer and the insurance company, Great West Casualty.  Great West Casualty contacted West Central Environmental Consultants out of Fridley, MN for cleanup.  The front compartment had a pin hole size leak in the compartment that began oozing out gasoline.  The front compartment also had the dome lid slowly leaking product due to the impact of the roll-over.  The dome lid's leak was stopped when given pressure on the dome lid by the owner Steve Steiger.
column169: The driver, Brian Pevito has participated in additional follow up driver training and driver awareness training to identify potential hazards involved with safe driving.  Brian has been put on probation for one year following this incident.  Within this year, Brian will be involved with ride alongs to monitor his driving skills, performance and implemented training.  Steiger Transport Inc. dba/Ratzlaff Transport has recertified Brian Pevito as a hazmat tanker driver.  Steiger Transport Inc. dba/Ratzlaff Transport has used this incident to add awareness and added training within the remaining entire fleet.
column198: Steiger Transport Inc. dba/ Ratzlaff Transport

ON MAY 18, 2014, A GASOLINE RELEASE OCCURRED FOLLOWING THE RUPTURE OF THE FUEL MANIFOLD ON A POPE TRANSPORT TANKER. THE MANIFOLD WAS DAMAGED WHEN THE TANKER CAME INTO CONTACT WITH A TELEPHONE POLE WHILE ATTEMPTING TO TURN INTO THE PARKING LOT OF A CIRCLE K CONVENIENCE STORE. THE FUEL WAS RELEASED TO THE ASPHALT SURFACE OF THE PARKING LOT AND ALONG THE CURBING OF PROVIDENCE ROAD. THE DRIVER PLACED BOOM AND ABSORBENT MATERIALS TO PREVENT THE GASOLINE FROM ENCOUNTERING SOIL, DRAINS, SURFACE WATER OR GROUND WATER. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR ALSO RESPONDED. ESTIMATED AMOUNT RELEASED WAS LESS THAN 24 GALLONS. THREE DRUMS OF ABSORBENT MATERIAL WERE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES.
column169: DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON OBSERVING FIXED STRUCTURES WHEN IN INGRESS AND EGRESS.

column14: PLEASANT VALLEY RD 50FT N OF C
column43: MOTOR FUEL, MOTOR SPIRITS, NATURAL GASOLINE, PETROL
column168: ON 5-9-14 AT 06:26 PACIFIC TANK LINES DRIVER WAS MAKING A LEFT TURN ONTO PLEASANT VALLEY RD. IN CAMARILLO CA. WHILE MAKING THE TURN OUR GASOLINE TANKER TRUCK ROLLED ONTO IT'S RIGHT SIDE LANDING ON THE CURB. FIRE AND POLICE WERE CALLED AND ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 06:35. FIRE REPORTED THAT THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT AT THIS TIME. PTL MANAGEMENT CONTACTED THE COMPANIES CONTRACTED ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN-UP COMPANY AND THEY WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. PTL MANAGEMENT MET WITH ON SCENE RESPONDERS FOR THE ACTION THAT WAS TO BE TAKEN, AT THIS TIME, DUE TO TEMPERATURE CHANGE, THE TRAILER REAR COMPARTMENT DOME LID BEGAN TO HAVE A SMALL SLOW LEAK, THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING INTO THE DIRT ADJACENT TO THE ROADWAY. THE TRAILER WAS DRILLED AND THE PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OFF. WHEN THE PUMPING OPERATIONS ENDED THE TRAILER WAS RIGHT AND TOWED FROM THE SCENE. VENTURA COUNTY FIRE TERMINATED THEIR RESPONSE AT 16:40 AND REPORTED THAT THERE WAS AN ESTIMATED 20 GALLON RELEASE. PATRIOT ENVIRONMENTAL BEGAN TO DIG UP THE AREA WHERE PRODUCT HAD LEAKED. CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS WERE SHUT DOWN DUE TO CONCERNS OF SHORING AND REQUIRED PERMITS. AS OF 8-7-14 ALL REQUIRED PERMITS AND CONTACTORS ARE TO START WORK ON GROUND TESTING AND REMEDIATION ON 8-13-14.
column169: IT WAS FOUND IN OUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION THAT THE ROLL OVER OCCURED DO TO DRIVER ERROR.  OUR DRIVER WAS PROPERLY TRAINED IN ROLL OVER PREVENTION.  THERE WERE SEVERAL CIRCUMSTANCES THAT CONTRIBUTED TO THIS INCIDENT; 1)DRIVER DID NOT FOLLOW THE RECOMMENDED JOURNEY PLAN, 2) THE VEHICLES COMPARTMENTS WERE NOT COMPLETELY LOADED (CAUSING A SLOSHING EFFECT), 3) CONTOUR/PROFILE OF THE ROADWAY (DOWNWARD SLOPE TO THE RIGHT) 4) INAPPROPRIATE SPEED (DRIVER SHOULD HAVE CUT THE SPEED IN HALF).      IMPROVED OPERATING PROCEDURES WOULD INCLUDE NO PARTIAL LOADED COMPARTMENTS.    IMPROVEMENT TO THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WOULD BE AN IMPLEMENTATION OF JOURNEY PLANS FOR ALL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: On Wednesday, May 21, 2014, FRA Inspectors Don Rhine and Roman Chavez conducted an Inspection in the Benson Yard. Upon my return from the field they briefed me on the defects they identified in the Yard. TILX 190045 was leaking product from the bottom outlet valve. I then instructed the Train Crew to switch the car into the unloading track. The car was emptied on May 23, 2014, then sent to home shop for repairs.
column169: I suggest a more thorough inspection prior to shipping would eliminate these issues.

column168: I WAS CALLED TO A LEAKING EXTENDO LEAKING OIL.  (GREEN BELT DOOR 74) AFTER DOING A PH TEST ON THE PUDDLE I CONFIRMED IT WAS AN ACID (READING "0") ON THE PH TAPE.  THEY MOVED THE TRAILER TO THE UNLOAD DOOR 5 WHERE MYSLEF AND KIM CHACON UNLOADED AND EVENTUALLY FOUND THE LEAKER WAS A CORROSIVE HAZMAT, SULFIC ACID.  WE GOT OUT ALL OF THE LAKED ON THE PACKAGES BROUGHT THEM  BACK TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA, SULFURIC ACID AND DEBRIS WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.  ALL ACID AND RESIDUE WAS NEUTRALIZED UPON CLEANING THE TRAILER.  LEO MARTINEZ WAS WORKING AS A SWEEP WHEN HE WAS WALKING UNDER A SLIDE, PACKAGE WAS AT TOP OF SLIDE AND LEAKING POURING DOWN ON HIM, CREATING BURNS/BLISTERS TO HIS BACK AND SHOULDERS.  HE WAS TAKEN TO FIRST MED AND THEN RELEASED SHORTLY AFTER AND RETURNED TO WORK.

column168: A PASSENGER HAD A BATTERY OPERATED WHEELCHAIR. DURING BOARDING AT CLE FOR FLIGHT US2709, HER NON TRAVELING COMPANION INCORRECTLY IDENTIFIED THE BATTERY AS A LITHIUM ION BATTERY AND IT WAS PLACED IN THE CABIN UNDER THE SEAT.  WHILE TRANSFERRING TO FLIGHT US1810 IN CLT, WHEN THE BATTERY WAS AGAIN STOWED UNDER THE SEAT, THE FLIGHT ATTENDANT WENT TO EXAMINE THE BATTERY TO VERIFY IT WAS APPROPRIATE FOR CABIN STOWAGE. UPON INSPECTION, THE BATTERY TURNED OUT TO BE A GLASS PACK NON-SPILLABLE BATTERY. DURING THE INSPECTION, THE BATTERY DID LEAK SOME MATERIAL (IDENTIFIED LATER AS PRIMARILY WATER, WITH SOME ACID). SINCE THE FA AND CAPTAIN TOUCHED THE BATTERY, THEY REQUESTED THAT THEY BE CHECKED AT THE HOSPITAL. THEY WERE TREATED FOR EXPOSURE TO THE ACID MIX ON THEIR HANDS.  THE FLIGHT WAS CANCELLED AND THE AIRCRAFT WAS TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE FOR INSPECTION. THE AIRCRAFT WAS CLEANED AND A SECTION OF CARPET WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED, AND THE AIRCRAFT RETURNED TO SERVICE LATER THAT NIGHT.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED REGARDING THE INCIDENT.
